	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If you found an obvious error on a Wikipedia page, why didn't you just fix it?</div><br />Because somebody is likely to revert it and use <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikilawyering" class="postlink">policy-fu</a> to keep your edit out. This happens especially often when the sources that <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources" class="postlink">score highly on Wikipedia's reliability metric</a> happen to be wrong. The reliability guidelines result from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" class="postlink">the verifiability policy</a> and are intended to keep out hoaxes but have occasionally counterintuitive consequences, such as <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2012/09/wikipedia-told-philip-roth-hes-not-credible-source-on-book-he-wrote/" class="postlink">an incident with Philip Roth</a>.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


